ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ…  Replication controler 
Replication Controller ensures that a specified number of pod replicas are always running.
If any pod fails or gets deleted, it automatically creates a new one.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ…  difference between ReplicaSet, Deployment, and StatefulSet and daemonSet in Kubernetes ğŸ‘‡

 1ï¸âƒ£ ReplicaSet (RS)                                                  # it is used in stateless application
Ensures a specific number of identical pods are always running.
âœ” Auto-restart
âœ” Auto-scale
âŒ No rolling updates
âŒ No version control
âŒ No stable network identity
ğŸ‘‰ Used inside Deployment automatically.
ğŸ‘‰ You rarely create ReplicaSet directly.

âœ… 2ï¸âƒ£ Deployment                                                         # it is used in stateless application
Manages ReplicaSets + provides rolling updates and rollbacks.
 in this we have extra features like rollback and rolling update 
  Deployment in Kubernetes is a higher-level resource that manages the deployment and lifecycle of your applicationâ€™s pods. 
  It allows you to define the desired state of your application, such as the number of replicas, 
  the version of the application, and how updates should be rolled out. Kubernetes then takes care of ensuring that the current state matches the desired state.
				
  Automatically running a specified number of copies (pods) of your app.
  Ensuring that the right version of the app is always running.
  Allowing you to easily update the app and automatically handle any failures or rollbacks.
âœ” Rolling updates
âœ” Rollbacks
âœ” Version control
âœ” Easy to scale
âŒ No unique identity
âŒ Not for database-type workloads
ğŸ‘‰ Best for stateless applications like:
Nginx
Node.js
Python
Java apps
APIs

âœ… 3ï¸âƒ£ StatefulSet
Used for stateful applications where each pod needs a fixed identity.
âœ” Stable pod name (pod-0, pod-1...)     # If a Pod crashes or is deleted, Kubernetes recreates it with the same name.
âœ” Stable network identity
âœ” Stable storage (PVC per pod)
âœ” Ordered startup & shutdown
âŒ Slower scaling
âŒ Not needed for stateless apps
ğŸ‘‰ Used for databases:
MySQL
MongoDB

apiVersion: apps/v1                  # API group/version that supports StatefulSet
kind: StatefulSet                   # Declares this object as a StatefulSet (for stateful apps)
metadata:
  name: mysql                       # Name of the StatefulSet (pods: mysql-0, mysql-1, mysql-2)
spec:
  serviceName: mysql                # Headless Service name (required for stable DNS)
                                    # Enables mysql-0.mysql, mysql-1.mysql, etc.
  replicas: 3                       # Number of MySQL pods to run
  selector:                         # Defines which pods this StatefulSet manages
    matchLabels:
      app: mysql                    # Pods with this label belong to this StatefulSet
  template:                         # Pod template (used to create each pod)
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: mysql                  # Pod label (must match selector above)
    spec:
      terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30
                                    # Time (seconds) given to MySQL to shut down gracefully
                                    # Prevents data corruption
      containers:
      - name: mysql                 # Container name inside the pod
        image: mysql:8.0            # Docker image pulled from Docker Hub
                                    # mysql = repository, 8.0 = version tag
        ports:
        - containerPort: 3306       # MySQL default port inside the container
          name: mysql               # Named port (used by Service)
        env:                        # Environment variables passed to MySQL
        - name: MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD # Sets root password (required to start MySQL)
          value: rootpassword       # Plain text password (use Secret in production)
        - name: MYSQL_DATABASE      # Database created automatically at startup
          value: appdb
        - name: MYSQL_USER          # Non-root user created automatically
          value: appuser
        - name: MYSQL_PASSWORD      # Password for the non-root user
          value: apppassword
        volumeMounts:
        - name: mysql-data          # Volume name (must match PVC template below)
          mountPath: /var/lib/mysql # Directory where MySQL stores its data files
  volumeClaimTemplates:             # Template for PersistentVolumeClaims
                                    # Kubernetes creates ONE PVC per pod
  - metadata:
      name: mysql-data              # Base PVC name
                                    # Actual PVCs:
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-0
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-1
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-2
    spec:
      accessModes:
      - ReadWriteOnce               # Volume can be mounted by only ONE pod
                                    # Required for databases
      storageClassName: my-storage-class
                                    # Storage provisioner used
                                    # Example: gp3, standard, local-path
      resources:
        requests:
          storage: 10Gi             # Disk size allocated PER pod
                                    # Total storage = 3 Ã— 10Gi

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
ğŸ” What is a Secret?
A Secret stores sensitive data such as:
Passwords
Tokens
Keys
Why use it?
Avoid hardcoding passwords in YAML
Better security
Can be rotated without changing app code
ğŸ‘‰ Examples:
MySQL root password
DB user password

2ï¸âƒ£ Create Secret (MySQL passwords)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: mysql-secret
type: Opaque
stringData:
  MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: rootpassword
  MYSQL_PASSWORD: apppassword

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âš™ï¸ What is a ConfigMap?
A ConfigMap stores non-sensitive configuration such as:
App settings
DB names
Environment values
Config files
ğŸ‘‰ Examples:
Database name
MySQL user
Application config values

1ï¸âƒ£ Create ConfigMap (MySQL configuration)
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: mysql-config
data:
  MYSQL_DATABASE: appdb
  MYSQL_USER: appuser


3ï¸âƒ£ Updated StatefulSet using ConfigMap + Secret
âŒ Before (BAD â€“ hardcoded)
env:
- name: MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD
  value: rootpassword

âœ… After (GOOD â€“ secure + clean)
envFrom:
- configMapRef:
    name: mysql-config
- secretRef:
    name: mysql-secret

4ï¸âƒ£ Full StatefulSet (only env section changed)
containers:
- name: mysql
  image: mysql:8.0
  ports:
  - containerPort: 3306
    name: mysql
  envFrom:
  - configMapRef:
      name: mysql-config
  - secretRef:
      name: mysql-secret
  volumeMounts:
  - name: mysql-data
    mountPath: /var/lib/mysql




âœ… One-line summary

ConfigMap stores configuration, Secret stores credentials, and both are injected into pods as environment variables for 
secure, maintainable Kubernetes deployments.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ… DaemonSet                                         # it is used in stateless application
DaemonSet ensures that exactly one pod runs on every node (or on selected nodes).

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ…  what is jobs in kubernetes
    job is used in k8s to Runs a pod until the task finishes              (written in .yml repo)
2ï¸âƒ£ Retry Job
A job that runs a command which fails, and Kubernetes retries it 4 times until it succeeds or reaches limit.
3ï¸âƒ£ Multi-Run Job
A job that runs the same task 3 times, one after another, until all are completed successfully.
4ï¸âƒ£ Parallel Job
A job that runs 5 tasks, but only 2 pods run at the same time (parallel batch processing).
5ï¸âƒ£ Database Backup Job
A job that starts a container once, runs a mysqldump command, saves the database backup, and then exits.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ… pods defferent states or lifecycle
creatingcontainer
running
completed
terminating
imagepullbackoff

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ…  cronjob             for this also we need to create .yml (written in .yml repo)
it is used to schedule the job/task               for this also we need to create .yml (written in .yml repo)
cronjob      =      *       *       *       *       *
                   min     hour    day  DayOweek  DayOmonth        

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
wwhy we need PV and PVC 
wwhen a pod is crached or deleted the data wwill gone But your data should NOT be deleted when pods are deleted.
So Kubernetes needs a separate storage system that lives independently of pods.

âœ… PV and PVC 
âœ… PV =  A PersistentVolume (PV) is a piece of storage in the cluster
Policy	
Retain	Keep data even after PVC deleted
Delete	Delete underlying storage when PVC deleted

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: pv-demo
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 5Gi
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain
  hostPath:
    path: /mnt/data   # local storage path on node (for demo)

âœ… PVC = A PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) is a request for storage by a pod.   ( means firstly wwe need to create the PV and then we need to claim that PV it is called PVC )
 Admin creates PV (cluster storage available)
User creates PVC (pod asks for storage)
Kubernetes matches PVC to a PV
Pod uses PVC to mount storage
Data persists even if pod dies or is recreated

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: pvc-demo
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 5Gi

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
âœ… How pods/deployments use PVC 
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: pod-using-pvc
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: busybox
    command: ["sh", "-c", "echo Hello > /data/hello.txt && sleep 3600"]
    volumeMounts:
    - name: storage
      mountPath: /data
  volumes:
  - name: storage
    persistentVolumeClaim:
      claimName: pvc-demo


âœ… after all this if we go to the path /mnt/data in node where the pod is running ( assume this pod is running on workernode1 that is a container ) 
   so we go inside that container and we can see the data in /mnt/data 

