services are used to expose the pod/deployment on web/internet 


ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½

1 What is Kubernetes and what does it do?
  It is a Open-Source Container Orchestration Tool 
		- Kubernetes is used to Deploy any type of Containers.
		- It is used to ensure high availability of the Applications/services running thru Containers.
		- Used to Ensure High Availability of Containers by creating Replicas of Containers.
		- It supports Auto-Scaling & Load Balancing.
		- Self-Healing

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
2 How are Kubernetes and Docker linked?
  Docker is focused on creating and running containers while kubernetes is used to
  deploy that container and ensure high availability load balancing auto-scaling and self healing 

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
3 List the features of Kubernetes. 
  Self-Healing: Restarts or replaces failed containers.
  Horizontal Scaling: Automatically scales applications based on demand.
  Load Balancing: Allows containers to find and communicate with each other.
  Rollouts and Rollbacks: Manages updates and can revert to previous versions if needed.
  Storage Orchestration: Manages persistent storage for containers.
  Namespace Support: Organizes resources for different teams or projects.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
4 What are clusters in Kubernetes?
  A Kubernetes cluster is a collection of nodes (machines) that work together, with the control plane managing and 
  coordinating the worker nodes. 
  The cluster is responsible for running and managing applications in containers, 
  ensuring high availability, scalability, and reliability.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
5 What do you know about Kubectl?
  kubectl (short for Kubernetes control) is the command-line tool used to interact and manage Kubernetes clusters. 

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
6 What is a node in Kubernetes?
   A node in Kubernetes is a machine (physical or virtual) that runs containerized applications. 
  There are two types of nodes: Master nodes that manage the cluster, and Worker nodes that run the applications.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
7 List the main components of Kubernetes architecture.
 The Kubernetes architecture consists of two main parts:
  Control Plane: Manages the cluster and makes global decisions (API Server, Scheduler, Controller Manager, etcd).
  Node (Worker Node): Runs containers and workloads (Kubelet, Container Runtime, Kube Proxy, Pods).

            API_Server 				--> # Acts as an interface to the kubernetes or we can say it is the brain + entry gate of the Kubernetes cluster.
            ETCD 				--> # Single point of Source for Kubernetes Components or we can say it is a data source for the cluster
	        Controller Manager 	         	--> # To run the pods in its desired state 
            Scheduler				--> # To identify the Healthy Node for Deployments
	        Kubelet 				--> # Is a Kubernetes Agent used to Create & Deploy the Pods	
	        CRI - Container RunTime Interface (Container-D) --> # It is used identify the Image from Container Registry for deployment
            KubeProxy				--> # it enable communication between pods and services, inside and outside the cluster.
                                             Pod IPs are assigned by the CNI plugin (like Flannel, Calico, Weave)
You run: kubectl apply -f deploy.yaml
kubectl sends request â†’ API Server
API Server validates YAML
Saves state in etcd
Scheduler gets notified
Scheduler selects a node
Kubelet on that node creates the pod

API Server stores state â†’ Controller Manager checks â†’ Scheduler assigns â†’ Kubelet runs â†’ Kube-Proxy connects â†’ Repeat forever.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
8 List the different types of services in Kubernetes.
  ClusterIP: The ClusterIP service is used to expose a service only within the Kubernetes cluster, not to the outside world.
             Backend Pod needs to talk to Database Pod
             Frontend Pod needs to talk to Backend Pod
             Microservices communicate internally

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-service
spec:
  selector:
    name: MyApp
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 9376
  type: ClusterIP

a ClusterIP service cannot be accessed directly from a browser; you must use "kubectl port-forward" (or another in-cluster access method).
kubectl port-forward svc/my-service 8080:80

  NodePort: Exposes your service outside the cluster by opening a port on every node.
            For testing
            When you donâ€™t have a cloud LoadBalancer
            Small environments or labs
            Not good for production because:
               Port range is limited (30000â€“32767)
               No automatic load balancing
               Must enter IP + NodePort manually
  LoadBalancer: Provisions an external load balancer, exposing the service to the internet.
             You want public access
             Want automatic load balancing across nodes
            Not ideal when: 
            You create many services â†’ each gets a public IP (costly)
            You want routing on paths/domains â†’ not supported
  ExternalName: it is used to connect with external resource like database API
Ingress (Domain + routing + rules)
ğŸ“Œ What it does:
Ingress gives:
Domain name support
URL path routing
TLS/HTTPS
Single public IP for many services

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Q To see all the resource pod/deployment/service
kubectl get all -n <namespace>


ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
9 What is Ingress network?
  ingress is a traffic controler in lkubernetes which is used to send the traffic or route the traffice to the right service in kubernetes cluster
  Ingress helps direct incoming internet traffic to the right service inside the cluster. For example, if someone visits example.com/api, 
  Ingress will send that request to your "API" service, and if they visit example.com/blog, Ingress will send it to the "Blog" service

  Single Entry Point:
  Instead of creating a separate entry for each service (like exposing each one with its own IP address), 
  you can use Ingress to create one entry point (one IP or domain) that handles traffic for all your services. This simplifies the setup.
  Ingress is like a traffic controller that makes sure the right visitors (users) get directed to the right service in your Kubernetes cluster.
  It helps you manage access through one main entry point (a single IP or domain).
  It can handle things like routing, load balancing, and security (SSL encryption).

firstly we need to Install an Ingress Controller
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes/ingress-nginx/main/deploy/static/provider/cloud/deploy.yaml

verify
kubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx

after that we need to Create the different Services in this namespace (nginx) for that we need to create deployment in same namespace(nginx) first and after that create 
service for that deployment in same namespace(nginx)    we can create multiple svc like for mobile,clothes,accessories, all so on and all that services run in same namspace


apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: minimal-ingress
  annotations:
    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: /
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx-example
  rules:
  - http:
      paths:
      - path: /mobile
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: mobile
            port:
              number: 80
      - path: /clothes
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: clothes
            port:
              number: 8080

after that we need to expose or forward the ingress controller svc
kubectl port-forward svc/ingress-nginx-controller -n ingress-nginx 8080:80

so now wwe can add multiple services in ingress  it is called microservices

Deleting a namespace deletes all workloads and networking objects inside it, immediately making the application inaccessible.
Yes, a single kubectl delete namespace can shut down everything, unless you put safeguards in place. Hereâ€™s how this is prevented in real-world clusters.

kubectl auth can-i delete namespaces --all-namespaces

1ï¸âƒ£ RBAC (MOST IMPORTANT) ğŸ”
Restrict who can delete namespaces

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
10 egress
  While Ingress controls incoming traffic to the cluster, Egress controls outgoing traffic of the cluster.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
30 How do you set resource limits on Kubernetes Pods?
   we can limit flag in yaml file to limit the resource on pods  like cpu and memory usage 
   or we can also request for memory and cpu 

  Memory Limits: If a container exceeds its memory limit, it will be terminated and potentially restarted by Kubernetes.
  This is called an OOM (Out of Memory) Kill.
  CPU Limits: When a container exceeds its CPU limit, it will be throttled (i.e., Kubernetes will restrict the container's 
  CPU usage but will not kill it).

resources:
  requests:
    cpu: "500m"        # Guaranteed CPU
    memory: "1Gi"      # Guaranteed memory
  limits:
    cpu: "1"           # Max CPU allowed
    memory: "2Gi"      # Max memory allowed

containers:
- name: mysql
  image: mysql:8.0
  resources:
    requests:
      cpu: "500m"
      memory: "1Gi"
    limits:
      cpu: "1"
      memory: "2Gi"

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
What are Probes in Kubernetes?
Probes tell Kubernetes when to start traffic, restart containers, and check health of your application.
They are critical for production workloads.
ğŸ”¹ Types of Probes (VERY IMPORTANT)
1ï¸âƒ£ Liveness Probe
ğŸ‘‰ Is the container alive?
If it fails â†’ container is restarted
Used to recover from deadlocks

2ï¸âƒ£ Readiness Probe
ğŸ‘‰ Is the container ready to receive traffic?
If it fails â†’ traffic is stopped
Pod is NOT restarted

3ï¸âƒ£ Startup Probe
ğŸ‘‰ Is the app finished starting up?
Disables liveness until startup completes
Prevents premature restarts

ğŸ§  Real-world behavior
Probe	Fails â†’
Liveness	Container restart
Readiness	Traffic removed
Startup	Startup still in progress
ğŸ”§ Probe methods
exec (run command inside container)
httpGet
tcpSocket

exec Probe
An exec probe is used to check application health by running a command inside the container
What itâ€™s used for (real-world)
Databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Redis)

livenessProbe:
  exec:
    command:
    - sh
    - -c
    - mysqladmin ping -h 127.0.0.1 -u root -p$MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD
  initialDelaySeconds: 60
  periodSeconds: 10
  timeoutSeconds: 5
  failureThreshold: 3

readinessProbe:
  exec:
    command:
    - sh
    - -c
    - mysqladmin ping -h 127.0.0.1 -u root -p$MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD
  initialDelaySeconds: 30
  periodSeconds: 5
  timeoutSeconds: 3
  failureThreshold: 3

startupProbe:
  exec:
    command:
    - sh
    - -c
    - mysqladmin ping -h 127.0.0.1 -u root -p$MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD
  failureThreshold: 30
  periodSeconds: 10

httpGet Probe 
An HTTP probe checks application health by sending an HTTP request to a container endpoint.
Where HTTP probes are used
âœ… Web apps (Nginx, Spring Boot, Node.js)
âŒ Databases (MySQL, Redis)

livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /
    port: 80
  initialDelaySeconds: 10
  periodSeconds: 10

readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /
    port: 80
  initialDelaySeconds: 5
  periodSeconds: 5

startupProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 8080
  failureThreshold: 30
  periodSeconds: 10


STEP 1ï¸âƒ£ Deploy BLUE (current live version)
blue-deployment.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp-blue
  namespace: prod
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
      version: blue
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
        version: blue
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: myapp
        image: myapp:v1
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
        readinessProbe:
          httpGet:
            path: /
            port: 80
          initialDelaySeconds: 5
          periodSeconds: 5

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
31 Explain Kubernetes taints and tolerations.
  Taints and Tolerations are a way to control where pods can run in a Kubernetes cluster.
taints- like we can taints a nodes(worker-node) so if we taints a node than pod can not run on that node
kubectl taint nodes node1 role=db:NoSchedule
kubectl taint nodes node1 role=db:NoSchedule-               # '-' it used to untained means now pod can run on this pod

tolerance- but if we still want to run the pod on taints node for that we use tolerance.
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: mysql-pod
spec:
  tolerations:
  - key: "role"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "db"
    effect: "NoSchedule"
  containers:
  - name: mysql
    image: mysql:8.0

so now pod can still run node1     # or we can say we can run the pod on taints node using tolerations in menifest file

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
HPA (Horizental Pod Autoscalling)
Increases or decreases the number of pods

apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: web-hpa
  namespace: Autoscalling  
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: web
  minReplicas: 2
  maxReplicas: 10
  metrics:
  - type: Resource
    resource:
      name: cpu
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 70

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscalling)
Adjusts CPU & memory requests automatically

we need to download VPA for that we can go to google and search 'kubernetes VPA' 

apiVersion: autoscaling.k8s.io/v1
kind: VerticalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: web-vpa
  namespace: Autoscalling
spec:
  targetRef:
    apiVersion: "apps/v1"
    kind: Deployment
    name: web
  updatePolicy:
    updateMode: "Auto"
  resourcePolicy:
    containerPolicies:
    - containerName: "*"
      minAllowed:
        cpu: "200m"
        memory: "256Mi"
      maxAllowed:
        cpu: "2"
        memory: "4Gi"

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Q  k8s Metrics
Metrics Server scrapes resource metrics from the kubelets running on each node and provides them in a central API endpoint (/apis/metrics.k8s.io/).
CPU usage (millicores)
Memory usage (bytes)

so firstly we need to install metrics server 
1st run this
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml

2nd
kubectl -n kube-system edit deployment metrics-server                # this will open a file so edit that file 
Add these args under containers.args:
- --kubelet-insecure-tls
- --kubelet-preferred-address-types=InternalIP,ExternalIP,Hostname

3rd
kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep metrics-server
kubectl top nodes
output-
NAME	CPU(cores)	CPU%	MEMORY(bytes)	MEMORY%
node1	  120m	     6%	       1024Mi	      25%
node2	  250m	     12%	   2048Mi	      50%

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Node Affinity
Node affinity is a Kubernetes feature that lets you control which nodes a Pod is allowed or preferred to run on, based on labels on nodes.
Run this Pod only (or preferably) on nodes that match certain conditions.â€
Node affinity lets you tell Kubernetes where Pods should (or must) run based on node labels.
affinity:
  nodeAffinity:
    preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
      - weight: 1
        preference:
          matchExpressions:
            - key: zone
              operator: In
              values:
                - ap-south-1

now the pod is creating only in ap-south-1 Zone 

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
RBAC (Role Base Access Control)
RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) in Kubernetes controls who can do what on which resources in the cluster.
Think of it like this:
WHO (user/service account)
CAN DO WHAT (verbs like get, create, delete)
ON WHICH RESOURCES (pods, services, deployments)
IN WHICH SCOPE (namespace or cluster)

Namespace-level RBAC (MOST COMMON)
firstly we need to create the role
then we need to create ServiceAccount 
then we need to binding role to serviceAccount 
then add to pod/deployment
Role â†’ ServiceAccount â†’ RoleBinding â†’ Pod                      #Users are for humans.
                                                                ServiceAccounts are for applications (bots, pods).
role
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  name: pod-reader
  namespace: dev
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods"]
  verbs: ["get", "list"]

service aacount
kubectl create serviceaccount app-sa -n dev

Role Binding 
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: pod-reader-binding
  namespace: dev
subjects:
- kind: ServiceAccount
  name: app-sa
  namespace: dev
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: pod-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

pod
spec:
  serviceAccountName: app-sa

Cluster-level RBAC (IN-CLUSTER / GLOBAL ACCESS)
ClusterRole â†’ ServiceAccount â†’ ClusterRoleBinding â†’ Pod

using Cluster role we can create dashbaords
Dashboards are created to provide a visual, centralized view of a system so humans can monitor, understand, and manage it easily.
Dashboards exist to help humans see and manage whatâ€™s happening inside the cluster without using only CLI commands.
ClusterRole is used for controllers, operators, monitoring, networking, and any component that needs cluster-wide or node-level access, not just dashboards.â€

BIGGEST difference
Feature                     	Namespace-level	                                  Cluster-level
Scope	                      One namespace only	                            Entire cluster
Affects	            Pods, Services, ConfigMaps in that namespace	   Nodes, PVs, Namespaces, all resources
Risk	                            Low	                                             High (powerful)


kubectl auth can-i create pods
kubectl auth can-i delete pods -n dev            # it used by user 
kubectl auth can-i get/delete/create/apply/watch/update/list pods/deployment/service/hpa/vpa/secrets/configmaps --as=pod-reader -n dev     #it is used by k8s admin 

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Custom Resource Defination(CRDs)
Using CRDs, we can create our own custom resources in Kubernetes just like Pods, Services, or Deployments.
Create CRD â†’ Create Custom Resources â†’ Interact with CR like native resource


ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
11 Differentiate between a replica set and a replication controller.
  ReplicaSet and ReplicationController are both Kubernetes resources used to ensure that a specified number of replicas of a pod are running at any given time, 
  ReplicaSet is an updated and more flexible version of ReplicationController, introduced in Kubernetes 1.2.
  we have extra features in replicaset like we can set a label no rolling upddate 

