When you should use Docker Scout 
Docker Scout helps you know whatâ€™s inside your Docker image, find security issues, and keep it safe over time.
docker scout quickview myimage:latest

ğŸ” Vulnerability scanning
ğŸ‘‰ It checks your Docker image for security problems
Looks inside your image layer by layer
Finds known security bugs (CVEs)
Tells you how serious each problem is
Shows which problems are easy to fix and which are not
ğŸ’¡ Think of it like a virus scan for your Docker image
docker scout cves myimage:latest

ğŸ§± Software Bill of Materials (SBOM)
ğŸ‘‰ It makes a list of everything inside your image
Lists all OS packages (like Linux tools)
Lists all app libraries (like npm, pip, etc.)
Helps you know exactly what software you are shipping
ğŸ’¡ Like a shopping bill showing every item in your container
docker scout sbom myimage:latest

ğŸ”„ Base image recommendations
ğŸ‘‰ It checks if your base image is safe and up to date
Warns you if your base image is old or risky
Suggests better, safer, or smaller images
Tells you whether problems come from:
the base image, or
your own application
ğŸ’¡ Like saying: â€œThe problem is in the foundation, not your house.â€

ğŸ“ˆ Continuous monitoring
ğŸ‘‰ It keeps watching your image even after you build it
Monitors your image over time
Alerts you if new security problems are discovered later
Works with Docker Hub and CI/CD pipelines
ğŸ’¡ Like a security guard that keeps checking your image every day

docker scout compare myimage:old myimage:new

