ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Helm                        # to download the helm we can go for official documentation
Helm simplifies deploying and managing apps in Kubernetes by packaging all resources together.

Helm lets you install, upgrade, and delete apps with one command
Helm is like a package manager for Kubernetes.
Just like npm installs JavaScript packages Or pip installs Python packages
Helm installs apps on Kubernetes in a structured way.

to create helm
helm create helm-name (apache-helm) 

. Install Helm
helm version   # check
brew install helm   # Mac

2. Create a Chart
helm create myapp 

3. Configure Values
Edit values.yaml for image, replicas, service type, etc.

4. Update Templates (Optional)
Edit files in templates/ if needed (e.g., deployment.yaml).

5. Install the Chart
helm install myapp-dev/prod/staging ./myapp
helm install myapp-dev/prod/staging ./myapp -n dev/prod/staging --create-namespace

Increase Number of Replicas
Edit values.yaml (or environment-specific values file):
replicaCount: 4
helm upgrade myapp-dev ./myapp -n dev -f values-dev.yaml

Use --set directly in command
helm upgrade myapp-dev ./myapp -n dev --set replicaCount=4

Rollback a Release
If an upgrade causes problems, you can rollback to a previous release version.
List revision history:
helm history myapp-dev -n dev
Shows revision numbers and timestamps.

helm rollback myapp-dev <revision-number> -n dev
helm rollback myapp-dev 2 -n dev

6. Upgrade Chart
helm upgrade myapp-dev/prod/staging ./myapp -n dev/prod/staginge

7. Uninstall Chart
helm uninstall myapp-dev/prod/staging -n dev/prod/staging

8. Package Chart (Optional)
helm package myapp

myapp/
  Chart.yaml          # Chart metadata   #This file contains basic information about your Helm chart, like its name, version, and description. Itâ€™s required for every chart.
  values.yaml         # Default configuration values #replicaCount â†’ Number of pods, image.repository â†’ Docker image name, image.tag â†’ Version, service.type â†’ clusterip,NodePort
  charts/             # Subcharts (dependencies)
  templates/          # Kubernetes manifest templates
  .helmignore         # Files to ignore in packaging

A Spring Boot app on Kubernetes mainly uses Deployment, Service, Ingress, ConfigMap, Secret, HPA, and Monitoring resources, all managed easily using Helm.

If a required Kubernetes resource is not present in the Helm chart, we add a new template YAML file under templates/, parameterize it using values.yaml, and deploy
it using helm upgrade.

Why Do We Use Helm Repositories?
We use Helm repositories to store, version, share, and reuse Helm charts so applications can be installed consistently across environments.

helm install myapp ./myapp
ğŸ‘‰ Only works if the chart exists locally.

Benefits of Using Helm Repo
Package Chart (Optional)
helm package myapp

1ï¸âƒ£ Centralized Storage
Charts stored in one central place
Everyone installs from the same source
Example:
helm install myapp myrepo/myapp

2ï¸âƒ£ Version Control
Each chart has versions:
myapp-1.0.0.tgz
myapp-1.1.0.tgz

Allows:
Easy upgrades
Safe rollbacks

3ï¸âƒ£ Easy Sharing Across Teams
Dev, QA, Prod teams use the same chart
No need to copy files manually

Create Helm chart in repo
Customize templates
Git version control & tag
Package chart
Publish to Helm/OCI repo
Install with helm install elsewhere

for git
if we use git for version controle we can push to git and whenever we need for reuse we can git clone and got to dir and install helm

for dockerhub
helm registry login registry-1.docker.io
helm package myapp
myapp-0.1.0.tgz
helm push myapp-0.1.0.tgz oci://registry-1.docker.io/<dockerhub-username>
helm install insureme \
  oci://registry-1.docker.io/mukunddeotale49/myapp \
  --version 0.1.0 \
  -n prod --create-namespace

OCI = Open Container Initiative

helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update
helm install monitoring prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack -n monitoring --create-namespace

helm repo add grafana https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update
helm install grafana grafana/grafana -n monitoring --create-namespace

kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-grafana 3000:80 -n monitoring
Login  and add data source in grafana as prometheus

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
Init Container
Definition: A container that runs before the main container starts in a Pod.
Purpose: Perform setup tasks that must finish before the main app runs.
Example Use Cases
Initialize a database schema
Download config files
Wait for another service to be ready

Sidecar Container
Definition: A container that runs alongside the main container in the same Pod.
Purpose: Add auxiliary functionality like logging, monitoring, or proxying.
Example Use Cases
Push logs to ELK/Fluentd 
Metrics exporter (Prometheus)
Service mesh proxy (Istio Envoy)

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
what is service mesh 
A service mesh is an infrastructure layer that helps manage communication between microservices in a distributed application.

for service mesh we need a tool to do this (istio, linkerd)
For Kind
# Install Istio CLI
For Kubeadm
# Install Istio CLI

Istio is a traffic manager for microservices

Kubernetes runs containers: Kubernetes starts and keeps your app containers alive (example: runs frontend and backend pods).
Istio controls traffic: Istio decides how services talk to each other (example: send 90% traffic to backend v1 and 10% to v2).
Envoy enforces rules: Envoy proxies actually apply those decisions to requests (example: retry a failed request or block unauthorized calls).
Control plane manages Envoy: Istio control plane configures all Envoy proxies centrally (example: push new routing rules without redeploying apps).
Kiali visualizes everything: Kiali shows a live graph of services and traffic health (example: see frontend â†’ backend â†’ payment with errors and latency)

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
13 Explain the pod in Kubernetes.
  A Pod is the smallest unit in Kubernetes. It can hold:
  One container (like a single app).
  Or multiple containers that work together (like a team of apps that need to talk to each other).

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
14 deff btn pod and deployment 
  Pod: it is a smallest unit in kubernetes  A single instance of a container or application.
  Deployment: it is used to manages multiple Pods, handles scaling, rolling updates, rollback and ensures high availability.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
15 What do you know about clusters of containers in Kubernetes? 
  A Kubernetes Cluster consists of a control plane (master) and multiple worker nodes.
  Each node runs a container runtime (e.g., Docker, containerd) that runs Pods.
  Pods are the smallest deployable units in Kubernetes, and they can contain one or more containers.
  Kubernetes clusters provide features like scaling, self-healing, and load balancing for containerized applications, making them ideal for running large-scale distributed systems.

ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ï¿½
